She believed that this could be achieved through a combination of aggressive foreign policy, military preparedness, and a sense of humanitarian responsibility towards the native populations under British rule. This militaristic outlook aligned well with the era's prevailing attitude of the "civilizing mission," wherein imperialist nations believed it was their duty to bring progress and enlightenment to the territories they colonized.
